Introduction

In this lesson, we get to know some basic R commands and RStudio. For this purpose, an example data set is used: The PokÃ©mon data set (link) (for those wondering: in the following lessons, we use data sets of greater sociological interest). Letâs jump right in and open RStudio.

RStudio

After opening RStudio, you should see something like this:

If you only see three panes, press CTRL+SHIFT+N which should open another window. In addition, the panes might be aligned differently than it is the case in the image. Donât mind, I have customized my layout (Tools -> Global options -> Pane Layout). However, this is not necessary to follow the course. Either way, you should see four windows now:

  • Console
  • Untitled1
  • Files/Plots/Packages/Help/Viewer
  • Environment/History

The pane entitled Console gives you feedback whenever code is run. It also takes commands but never saves them. Just try and use it as a calculator:

1 + 2 * 4
## [1] 9

However, the problem that code is not saved is a huge drawback. Hence, we typically use Scripts when writing computer code. When we put something down in the pane Untitled1, we can re-run our code over and over again. Further, we can save it and edit it later on. This is the main window in RStudio.

Finally, we have a pane Environment where we can see what kind of objects we have created during our session. The last window Files serves multiple purposes. Among others, it is used to display plots that we create.

Prerequisites (Loading packages)

Most scripts in R start with loading data and additional packages that greatly expand on Râs functionality (link). Packages have to be installed only once but in order to use them they have to be loaded everytime R is started again. This can be done in the following way:

# Installs the package
install.packages(c("tidyverse", "rvest", "stringr", "ggplot2")) # Just some standard pkgs.

# Load the package
library(tidyverse)

However, as for many things in R, there is a package that makes installing and loading packages easier. The packages donât have to be put into quotation marks and pacman checks for newer version of the packages in one call.

library(pacman) # I assume the package has been installed before.
p_load(tidyverse, rvest, stringr, ggplot2)

Loading Data

R is able to load data from numerous formats including CSV, Excel, SPSS, Stata. I have downloaded the data before (see script: CatchEmAllCode_150917.R on Moodle) and saved into Râs data format .RDS. We can load the data with a simple command. At the same time, we use the assignment operator <- to save the result into an object that we name pokemon.df.

pokemon.df <- readRDS(file = "C:/Users/User/HU-Box/Seafile/Meine Bibliothek/Seminare/WS 2017/Code/Pokemon/data/PokemonData")

Take a look at the window titled âEnvironmentâ there should be a line saying pokemon.df. In addition, it gives some information on the data which has 151 observations and 12 variables. When you double-click this line, RStudio opens the data editor where one can inspect the data set. This could also be achieved by typing View(pokemon.df).

Congratulations! You have loaded your first data set (called data frame) into Râs memory. But how do we progress? Letâs play a little bit around with the data in order to get a feeling of it.

However, we also see which variables are in the data and we get a glance of the observations. We can see that the first PokÃ©monâs name is âBulbasaurâ which some of you might remember:

Râs data types

The PokÃ©mon data comes in a rectangular form which is the most common type of data in the social sciences. Nearly, all of our data comes as some kind of large table with columns representing variables and rows being observations. However, in R every object is made up of vectors.

We can create a simple vector on our own by concatenating together individual elements using c():

a.vector <- c(2, 4, 6, 8, 10)
a.vector
## [1]  2  4  6  8 10

Is the object we just created a vector?

is.vector(a.vector)
## [1] TRUE

Letâs check if a single element is also a vector:

is.vector(a.vector[1]) # Accessing the first element using brackets.
## [1] TRUE

Now, our data frame should also be a vector, right? Letâs ask R kindly to check and hopefully confirm our assumption:

is.vector(pokemon.df)
## [1] FALSE

Oh, no! What went wrong? Pokemon.df doesnât seem to be a vector. Letâs check whether the data frame is at least made up of vectors. We can access a variable in our data by typing the name of the data frame followed by a dollar sign and the name of the variable:

pokemon.df$Name[1:10] # The brackets ensure that only the first ten PokÃ©mons are displayed. 
##  [1] "Bulbasaur"  "Ivysaur"    "Venusaur"   "Charmander" "Charmeleon"
##  [6] "Charizard"  "Squirtle"   "Wartortle"  "Blastoise"  "Caterpie"

The same could be achieved by using brackets again. When doing so, the first number gives the row and the second number the column:

pokemon.df[1:10, 2] # Not shown.

Now, letâs test again if that is a vector:

is.vector(pokemon.df$Name)
## [1] TRUE

That seems to be the case. We can apply another function in order to check whether this is true for all columns/variables:

apply(X = pokemon.df, MARGIN = 2, FUN = is.vector) # Apply is a little bit tricky. Type '?apply' if you want to know more. 
##       #    Name    Type   Total      HP  Attack Defense Sp. Atk Sp. Def 
##    TRUE    TRUE    TRUE    TRUE    TRUE    TRUE    TRUE    TRUE    TRUE 
##   Speed   Type1   Type2 
##    TRUE    TRUE    TRUE
